Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment: This trailer have had a tone of the movie about how‚Äôs society responsible for the mad and corrupted nature of the villains . It starts with the scene where the government people act inhuman, the beginning of it filled with the different forms of cruelty and darkness( cutting meat in the dish, people in military uniform, all the places are dim). And when the Suicide squad members are starting to be shown - they all look lost and sad, even scared. All of them are in some uncomfortable trapped circumstances - Harley in the cage trying to reach light with her hand,Deadshot and El Diablo in the prison,  Killer Croc is even in the chains, Enchantress in this scary place aka bathtub. Opposite to the Waller who is sitting in perfectly comfortable restaurant saying that her duty is to manipulate people. All the villains are looking more like someone who gone mad from the cruelty of the world. ‚ÄúAre you the devil?‚Äù - says Harley Quinn when we see a shot of her looking at Amanda. We see this people ,who were shown alone in first part, come together in the scene where they are walking on the street. After that we hear  Deadshot speaking about their role in the story and only after that we starting to see them in real action. That is what it should‚Äôve been: a story about the world that only deserves villains, not heroes, where BAD guys are natural ‚Äòcause this are the rules of the reality, ‚Äòcause people who consider themselves GOOD are evil too. Trailer ends with the Joker who is the only villain in it that looks like he is a ‚Äúruler of his fate‚Äù, because he is purely insane and don‚Äôt even try to reach the light ( he even appeared from darkness in the scene). Shame that we got only a boring movie where all villains suddenly became heroes in a minute, with no plot, no philosophy, nothing. Thanks for the trailer at least.

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment:
To me Marvel comics always had the best and most lovable heroes, but DC was darker, and because it was darker it had the ability to create deep and incredible villains. DC understood that too, and they eventually released one of their most critically acclaimed line of comics ever. It was different, because instead of the heroes we've met, we watch the world from the perspective of all the villains we've been given incredible perspective on throughout all the series to that point. Harley Quinn, Diablo, Deadshot, even the Joker on occasions... What an experience.
Suicide Squad was an amazing comic, and it deserved to be an amazing movie. It deserved to be at least half of what this amazing trailer promised. It wasn't.
I call foul, and for a remake.

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment:
From a comic book fan's perspective, the biggest issues I ultimately had were the size of the team and their ultimate goal. 

For their first cinematic outing this, team was just too big. Harley and Joker should have been saved for a solo Batman film. Killer Croc and Katana didn't do anything to justify their presence (though they did have some cool scenes). Enchantress should have been saved for JLD or something else that revolves around magic. Diablo was fine, I just would have saved him for later, and Slipknot...yeah. I would have gone with a five man team. Flagg, Deadshot, Boomerang, Plastique, and Karen Grace. All from the comics, all have history with the squad. 

As for their goal, it's not unheard of for the squad to save the world, but they're not altruistic about it. Deadshot is still a cold hearted assassin, Boomer is still a piece of shit bigot. They only barely tolerate each other enough to get the job done so Waller won't kill them. Most times they're cleaning up the government's mess or doing things the government can't afford to be seen doing.

This was the movie that actually warranted a dark tone but because of the BvS fallout,  WB went full panic mode and over compensated.

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment: Looking back, you can see what the original movie was: It was about the theme of control. Enchantress gets free and attacks the city, prompting the suicide squad to be sent in. Enchantress attacks that city as a set up, so that she could draw Waller out, so she could get revenge on her. The point of the movie would have lead up to the team having to decide to either save Amanda Waller and go back to jail, or let enchantress kill Waller and have their freedom. If you remember, The Joker was supposed to be in that final scene, but was cut out. He was supposed to push Harley out of the copter, trying to kill her, a final betrayal before his copter crashes. Then in the final fight scene, the Joker would then show up, and try to take Harley. She'd then choose to reject him, and the team would choose to kill enchantress for being so dangerous, in spite of their treatment by Amanda Waller.

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment: The movie should've had the same vibe that was portrayed by this trailer, dark, vague, and melancholy. The next trailers after this one ruined the mood by having a lighter-comedic tone into it. They felt really saturated to where you couldn't feel the ambient atmosphere that this trailer offered, kind of like death was all around, and a message that not everyone was going to make it out alive in this movie, with this trailer. Unfortunately the movie did not live to its expectations, which why it wasn't the best movie within critics and viewers. Not to say it was bad, but definitely could've been way better, by a lot. The tone in the final movie was ruined by how edge-less it was, with corny jokes, childish humor, and a cliche script written by the director, who seemed like he was rushed. Not to mention the infamous plot story and etc. Made it seem like a Marvel movie to be truthful. I just wished they would've stuck with the darker, and malicious tone like this trailer, it made the whole environment heavy with ambiguity. Not to hate on the movie, but it's just my opinion. Eh.

If these miscreants can band together and complete their impossible mission: create a fun, profitable comicbook blockbuster utilizing a 70's pop soundtrack, they will be known from that day as the GUARDIANS OF- I mean, uh, SUICIDE SQUAD!"

-From Cracked

Comment:
I don't understand why everyone is saying this movie shouldn't be rated R. This movie doesn't need to be rated R at all. But from my own observation, I feel like the only reason people are saying that is because Deadpool got an R rating.

But here's the thing, the only reason Deadpool got an R rating is to stay as faithful to the comics as possible. Like he will in the movie, Deadpool swears, he uses very crude humor, when he cuts up bad guys, blood sprays out everywhere, basically, the comics are rated R as well.

There is NO violent R rated superhero trend going on here just because Deadpool got an R rating, that one needed it. This movie DOESN'T need it, it can be PG-13 and work perfectly fine. Dark Knight was plenty dark, and it worked just fine with a PG-13, so will this one. Everyone who is saying it should be rated R, don't get your hopes up, looks like it's gonna be PG-13.

I hope the film is as dark as the trailer, though I am doubting that, if its going to be pg13. If they could make it as dark, or darker than sin city for example. I mean, when you think of the characters there's potential for some really horrific scenes. You know that if these extreme characters were to exist in real life, joker would be torturing people in fucked up ways on the reg. 

If it is a pg13 i'm guessing this trailer is as dark as it gets, which makes me wonder - if you know the concept is strong enough to put in the trailer, why not produce the whole film that way? 

But at the end of the day making a film adhere to a lower rating expands your audience, expands your profit margin.. If they could make a pg-13 cut and an R-rated cut, that would be awesome.

Comment:
I'm really excited to see what they've done to "Killer Croc" and his character. Because he is simply one of the more deep and pitiable enemies of Batman, not just insane for the lulz like Joker. You see when Croc was little he was forced to live with an abusive and psychotic aunt who hated him(his mother had passed away by this time) and she would treat him horribly, beating him and locking him away. Was also bullied by other kids for his disease.  

Until one day Croc had enough and murdered her... After that he fled hos old home and joined a traveling freak show where he finally found acceptance and a sense of "family". It was not to last, for an angry mob attacked the freak show, and killed every single person Croc held dear to him. This enraged Croc, who went on a murder spree, slaughtering the angry mob for their actions. These events effectively drove Croc insane, turning him into "Killer" Croc .

Croc's mentality is he hates humanity, as a whole, and views US as evil. This is why Croc prefers to be seen as an animal or beast and actually takes offense at being referred to as "human" for he no longer sees himself as such, having divorced his humanity long ago. Yes, he is a super strong, cannibalistic mutant, psychopath... but can you really blame him?

Joel Kinnamen as Rick Flagg - Haven't seen much of him either, but hopefully he does great as the team's leader.

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment:
I'm not mad about Joker's design at all. Sure, we all have our favourite depiction of The Joker; but this version, despite some radical changes in his appearance, stays true to the core of the character. 

We have the green hair and the pale skin. This time it really looks like his skin is pale instead of wearing make-up.  Joker does have some very expressive eyebrows; but this time they are removed to emphasize on his disturbed look and focus more on his eyes; who are no less expressive.

To me, Joker has always been as flamboyant as he is psychotic, he likes to really stick out in appearance (and his pale skin and hair does more than enough in that category) by dressing himself in colourful garments. He also likes to put on a show when committing his heinous acts, such as decorating the whole Arkham Asylum for Batman's arrival or such things. Given to his flamboyant nature, I would say that those tattoos fit very well; he's really trying to say: LOOK AT ME! LOOK AT ME!.

But then comes the same old discussion: why would Joker get himself tattoo? How could such an insane man stay still and calm enough to have the tattoo complete? Wouldn't he just kill the tattoo artist?

Well, in the famous "Arkham Asylum: A Serious House On Serious Earth" story, written by Grant Morrison, an interesting hypothesis was made on Joker's personality; stating that Joker redefines his personality every day (which explains why he can be a psychotic murderer one day and a comparatively harmless mischievous clown the other). While still  only being a hypothesis, this has stuck to many fans' view on the character and this would totally explain why the Joker would even get himself a tattoo.

The silver-teeth/grills, or whatever you want to call it, shares the same purpose as the tattoos.

All in all, even though Joker is being reenvisioned again in this film; it still holds strong comic-book themes and features intact. In fact, this is probably the closest comic-book Joker put on film ever. Nicholson was a flamboyant gangster but never came off as truly insane. Ledger nailed the psychotic aspect of the character but I can't say that he felt very flamboyant. Leto might just be the version everyone needs.

Comment:
Holy schnapps... This Joker looks really evil.

Jack Nicholson portrayal of Joker was very nonchalant. He didn't care if you died or not, he just wanted to reach his end goal and if you were in his way or part of his plan, then goodbye. You're dead.

Heath Ledger Joker was very philosophical. His was views were kind of like Thomas Paine laws of governance... Basically, Heath Ledger portrayal of Joker forced us to question human nature and law. He killed people in a sense to test boundaries. I can't even explain it.

Jared Leto's Joker seems like the true psychopath how the comic portrays him to be. I know this just a trailer and don't know how he's really going to be portrayed but that small clip at the end was powerful. The feeling of knowing he is evil in a dark dark sinister way but tries to be funny and utterly failing.

Can't wait....

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment:
Reasons why SSQ Joker will be awesome:
1) Leto is a great actor, and while he hasn't been in many movies all his performances were solid. AA for DBC was well deserved.
2) Leto is a music star, therefore he is immune to drugs. That gives us a Joker for more than 1 movie
3) They don't give us a spin on Ledger's Joker, but a new approach to the character with lots of possibilities
4) No more 'realism' ala Nolan, so we can possibly have laughing poison and shit (TDK was awesome, but all this bombs and gasoline weren't the most imaginative thing on Earth)
5) The makeup is superb.

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment:
Just read an article of why SS has the upper hand on BVS and I must say, I do agree.

BVS is already predictable: Batman goes after Superman because of the events in MoS. They fight while Lex Luthor plots to take over Gotham and/or Metropolis and kill Superman with the possibility of wanting to kill Batman. Batman and Superman realise Luthor is the real enemy and then go after him together. They then succeed and start to form the Justice League with Wonder Woman. WW may be the one who makes them see that Luthor is the enemy, I dunno, but that's basically going to be the general outline of the film

SS. Apart from the SS going after Joker, the film is really unpredictable. Anything can happen. As in anything. The SS don't even have to succeed! The Joker could turn them all on each other or against Waller, Harley could go back to Joker, they could decide to kill Batman instead of Joker etc. So much can happen! 

I am looking forward to both films, but just thinking about the two films makes me just that bit more psyched for SS over BvS.

To all of you that don't read comics or don't know what this movie is suppose to be about, here's a quick synopsis:
In the world of superheroes, there are also supervillains. These villains get locked up in prison after being defeated by the heroes. Amanda Waller sees that these villains have great powers and abilities, they're just being used in the wrong way. So she goes to these prisons and recruits villains to work for her in dangerous black ops missions. How does she get them to work for her? She implants nano-bombs in their neck or heads. If they try to escape, disobey an order, or kill civilians or their teammates, she'll detonate the bombs. Whoever's alive by the end of the mission will have time taken off their sentence.

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment:
I swear I've been watching this trailer non stop since it first dropped lol.¬† If this movie ends up being a hit, then I guarantee DC will eventually find a way to incorporate some sort of Secret Six spin off too. Like David Ayer said, DC has the best villains and they've seemed to have finally made a serious commitment to exploring that strong aspect of their shared cinematic universe.¬† It's really hard to sell a dark and gritty universe as a whole, if you only make movies focusing on superheroes who obviously have a greater moral compass than most. You need a few movies focusing on the villains as the main aspect to really get the audience to fully understand how dark the overlining tone truly is for the entire DCCU.¬† This is probably also a big reason why they've decided to keep their tv and cinematic worlds separate.¬†

They figure the DC fans who want to see a more comedic light tone will still have all the tv shows to fall back on, while the fans of the dark and gritty obviously have the films to look forward too.¬† It's a very similar strategy but of an opposite tone to what Marvel is doing with their films and their Netflix shows.¬† The difference obviously being that unlike Marvel, the DCCU isn't connected with the DCTU, but again that's because DC obviously feels the general tone they want to show on film wouldn't translate as well in weekly procedural network TV form, especially since Marvel beat them to the punch with the Netflix deal. If you're a fan of both then it's really a win/win situation lmao.¬† Perhaps there's some chance they could connect tv with film if they decide at some point to do the whole multiverse thing for the films but right now that might just be way too complicated for them.

Title: Suicide Squad - Comic-Con First Look [HD]
Comment:
Leto is a phenomenal actor capable of great range. ¬†Very flexible in what he can portray. ¬†

It is just my prejudice and bias I suppose. ¬†I thought Nicholsons version was a masterpiece. ¬†He was having FUN, and had all kinds of toys. ¬†You could feel this character. ¬†I felt it was closer to what I knew to be the comic book version of the Joker.

Ledger brought some kind of darkness few characters have ever been able to bring to life. ¬†His Joker's genius was such that despite all the destruction, you couldnt be quite sure if he was in fact crazy, despite on the surface looking batshit crazy as fuck. ¬†I am probably wrong, but I never recalled a Joker looking anything like this. ¬†It seemed to me to be Ledgers own interpretation, and I fucking LOVED it. ¬†You felt this Joker to your bones. ¬†You could feel something real and primal here. ¬†By mid-movie he started to feel like a force of nature - Chaos. ¬†You knew epicness when you saw it here. ¬†He one-upped Jack. ¬†

Two TALL orders to beat. ¬†This guy was just supposed to be a villain. ¬†Now he is turning into something truly phenomenal, that makes actors try to draw on everything they have to give something better then what we had before. ¬†I am not sure that can be beat. ¬†We'll just have to see if he can give something the equal of the last 2.

This trailer left me curious as hell. ¬†There is potential for Leto to pull something off, but this was not enough to give any solid judgements by :D

Ugh. ¬†Why, why, WHY did they cast Will Smith in this!?!?¬†

Comment: For people criticizing the joker line, that joker would never say that and you put the blame and Leto... Just letting you know Leto speaks what's on the page, if you have a problem with the line, the correct criticism is "This script seems like garbage, the dialogue is not accurate towards the characters, and the Joker would never say that." You can't blame an actor for shit lines, generally speaking. A great actor can make a shit script average and a great script can make a shitty actor amazing. Now unless you're a troll, then well keep doing what you're doing, for others, concentrate on Leto's voice, body work, and facial expressions if you dislike the line. I'm so excited to see a new actor approach a familiar character because it's fresh and fun to analyze why they approach the character the way that they did and make it their own. Extremely excited for this, and also this is probably the best acting I've seen Will Smith do in a very long time, looks great. Very excited.
